r example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n179,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\" is a comprehensive system that tracks and accumulates the actual costs and revenues attributable to each product from its development through to its abandonment. This approach involves identifying the costs incurred at different stages of the product's life cycle, deriving a life-cycle cost or profit in both manufacturing and service industries, and recognizing the benefits of life-cycle costing. By tracking cumulative costs and revenues throughout the product's stages, life-cycle costing encourages management to plan the pricing strategy for a product over its entire life cycle. Additionally, it is an Environmental Management Accounting (EMA) technique that considers the total cost of ownership, including acquisition, operation, and disposal costs.\",11\n373,\"\"\"EMA TECHNIQUES\"\"\",\"\"\"EMA techniques include input/output analysis, ABC, and life-cycle costing.\"\"\",4\n1587,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR MIDHURST CO'S NEW AIR CONDITIONING UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Midhurst Co is considering an investment in a new air conditioning unit that utilizes advanced technology to efficiently regulate airflow and temperature, providing a competitive edge in the market. This new unit is designed for use in modern office buildings and is more sensitive to changes and variations in temperature, allowing it to regulate airflow and heating more efficiently than any current competitor products.\n\nThe company plans to use life-cycle costing to evaluate the unit's profitability, taking into account various costs over the product's predicted five-year life cycle. These costs include research and development ($6,200,000), design ($33,450,000), marketing ($177,685,000), variable production costs per unit ($42), fixed production costs ($98,470,000), variable distribution costs per unit ($9), fixed distribution costs ($10,300,000), variable selling costs per unit ($4), fixed selling costs ($7,790,000), and administration costs ($23,450,000). Midhurst Co expects to sell 10,000 units over this period.\n\nThe finance director has prepared the initial costings and plans to use life-cycle costing to measure the new product's profitability. The chief executive, who is seeking to understand the benefits of life-cycle costing for strategic decision-making, has requested more information about this method. Meanwhile, the production director has reviewed the costings in detail, suggested possible cost reductions, and is enthusiastic about the product. He believes that modifications could be made to extend the product's life cycle but is considering the optimal timing for these changes.\n\nOverall, Midhurst Co aims to leverage life-cycle costing to make informed strategic decisions regarding the new air conditioning unit, ensuring it remains competitive and profitable throughout its life cycle.\"\"\",4\n215,\"\"\"PRODUCT LIFECYCLE\"\"\",\"The product lifecycle consists of stages such as development, introduction, growth, maturity, and decline. It describes how demand conditions for a product, a brand, and whole markets change over time. Different pricing policies might be adopted at various stages to maximize profits and manage demand effectively.\",4\n1590,\"\"\"QUIZ ON LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves multiple questions about life-cycle costing, including the stages of the product lifecycle, cost per unit calculations, material cost revisions, and the implications for production planning. It also covers the advantages of using life-cycle costing for strategic decision-making.\"\"\",4\n216,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Zany developed a new computer game during the year 20X2 for $200,000. The game will be launched in the year 20X3. Budgeted revenues and costs of the game over its lifecycle are presented, showing how life-cycle costing estimates and accumulates costs over a product's entire lifecycle.\"\"\",1\n1246,\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTING QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz tests knowledge on life cycle costing, focusing on identifying costs over a product's entire life cycle and calculating overall profitability.\"\"\",1\n193,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle cost is the total cost of a product or service over its entire life-cycle, calculated in life-cycle costing.\"\"\",1\n192,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE STAGES\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle stages are different phases in the life of a product or service, from development to decline, considered in life-cycle costing.\"\"\",1\n194,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle profit is the total profit of a product or service over its entire life-cycle, calculated in life-cycle costing.\"\"\",1\n1367,\"\"\"LIFECYCLE PROFIT PER CUSTOMER\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz about calculating the lifecycle profit per customer for a new type of bank account.\"\"\",1\n726,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Full cost plus pricing\"\" is a long-term pricing strategy that ensures prices cover all variable and fixed costs. The price of a product using full cost plus pricing is calculated by adding a markup to the full cost per unit.\",6\n776,\"\"\"COST PLUS PRICING METHODS\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost plus pricing methods involve adding a given margin to the cost of a product. The cost may be the marginal cost, the full cost, or even the relevant cost.\"\"\",3\n738,\"\"\"QUIZ: COST PLUS AND TARGET ROI\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the selling price of a new product using different pricing strategies: full cost plus 20%, marginal cost plus 40%, and target ROI of 10%. It also includes a question on calculating profit if actual sales are below budget.\"\"\",3\n728,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages of full cost plus pricing include: profit will be made if the budget sales level is achieved, the full cost should be readily available if a system of standard costing is in operation, it is appropriate where fixed costs are significant, useful for justifying prices and price rises, and it is simple and cheap to operate.\"\"\",1\n729,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Disadvantages of full cost plus pricing include: the method of accounting for overheads will have a large impact on the costs calculated for different products, losses may occur if actual sales are below budget, it ignores external factors like demand/price relationship and competitors' prices, the size of the mark-up is arbitrary, and it may not maximize profits.\"\"\",1\n1271,\"\"\"QUIZ ON FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz tests knowledge on full cost plus pricing, including its appropriateness for long-term pricing and its ability to guarantee profit if budgeted sales levels are achieved.\"\"\",1\n725,\"\"\"PRICING DECISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"Pricing decisions involve factors influencing product pricing, price elasticity of demand, demand equations, optimum selling price, and various pricing strategies.\"\"\",1\n730,\"\"\"MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Marginal cost plus pricing is a short-term pricing strategy that involves calculating the selling price per unit by adding a mark-up percentage to the budgeted variable production and non-production costs.\"\"\",4\n734,\"\"\"RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI) PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"ROI pricing is a long-term pricing method where prices are set to achieve a target percentage return on the capital invested in production.\"\"\",4\n1589,\"\"\"BENEFITS OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle costing helps management plan pricing strategies over the entire product lifecycle, leading to better cost control and understanding. By monitoring cumulative revenues and costs, it provides more meaningful information for decision-making than traditional period-based monitoring. Additionally, it allows for cost reduction during the design phase, improving profitability and informed decision-making on product development and continuation.\"\"\",2\n1588,\"\"\"PRODUCT LIFECYCLE STAGES\"\"\",\"\"\"The product lifecycle consists of five stages: development, introduction, growth, maturity, and decline. During the development stage, the product is designed, and manufacturing processes are established, with negative cash flow as no revenue is generated. As the product moves through the introduction, growth, and maturity stages, pricing strategies evolve to maximize demand and profits, while in the decline stage, demand and prices may decrease unless a niche market is found.\"\"\",2\n775,\"\"\"PERFECT COMPETITION\"\"\",\"Perfect competition is a theoretical market structure characterized by many sellers and buyers, identical or homogeneous products, and no barriers to entry. In this market, there is perfect information available to all participants, meaning that all buyers and sellers have full knowledge of prices and products. The sale and purchase of goods occur at the market clearing (or equilibrium) price, where supply and demand are equal, ensuring there is no excess or shortage. Market participants in perfect competition are 'price takers,' meaning they must accept the market price and cannot influence it.\",2\n732,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: the mark-up represents contribution, which is useful in short-term pricing decisions like market penetration policy, and it treats fixed costs by their nature and not using an arbitrary allocation.\"\"\",1\n736,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF ROI PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages of ROI pricing include: it links price to both short-term costs and long-term capital employed, it is consistent with ROI as a performance measure, and the target ROI can be set to take account of risk.\"\"\",1\n773,\"\"\"COMPETITORS\"\"\",\"\"\"Competitors are other businesses offering similar products or services in the market. The presence of competitors can influence a company's pricing strategy and market power.\"\"\",1\n774,\"\"\"CUSTOMERS\"\"\",\"\"\"Customers are the buyers of a company's products or services. The relationship with customers, including dominant customers and bulk buying, can affect pricing strategies.\"\"\",1\n733,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Disadvantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: it may lead to failure to recover fixed costs, and it is not appropriate for long-term pricing, particularly where fixed costs are significant, because in the long-term, fixed costs may also vary and not be sufficiently covered by mark-up.\"\"\",1\n737,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF ROI PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Disadvantages of ROI pricing include: it ignores external factors, there are problems in calculating capital employed (e.g., whether to use book values or replacement cost), and there is a subjective split of shared investment between products.\"\"\",1\n374,\"\"\"SUSTAINABILITY AND BUSINESS RESILIENCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Accountants must be able to link sustainability to the broader business agenda by highlighting elements that build resilience and develop a sustainable strategy.\"\"\",1\n316,\"\"\"INPUT/OUTPUT ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Input/output analysis\"\" is a technique used in environmental management accounting (EMA) to track the flow of materials and energy through a system. It helps identify inefficiencies and areas for improvement.\",1\n731,\"\"\"MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING FORMULA\"\"\",\"\"\"Selling price per unit = (Budgeted Variable production cost + Budgeted Variable non-production cost + Mark-up) / Budgeted sales units\"\"\",1\n735,\"\"\"ROI PRICING FORMULA\"\"\",\"\"\"Selling price per unit = Budgeted full cost + (target ROI percentage x capital employed) / Budgeted sales units\"\"\",1\n777,\"\"\"OPPORTUNITY COST PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Opportunity cost (relevant cost) pricing is suitable for short-term pricing decisions.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n198,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing can be driven down by directing attention to any costs related to any part of a product's lifecycle, which is the concept of life-cycle costing.\"\"\",33\n122,\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\"\"\",\"\"\"EMA TECHNIQUES\"\"\",\"\"\"Activity-based costing (ABC) is an EMA technique.\"\"\",28\n212,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"EMA TECHNIQUES\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle costing is an EMA technique.\"\"\",15\n215,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR MIDHURST CO'S NEW AIR CONDITIONING UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-Cycle Costing and Strategic Planning for Midhurst Co's New Air Conditioning Unit is related to Life-Cycle Costing.\"\"\",15\n210,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"PRODUCT LIFECYCLE\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle costing involves tracking costs and revenues over the entire product lifecycle, from development to abandonment.\"\"\",15\n216,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ ON LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz on Life-Cycle Costing is related to Life-Cycle Costing.\"\"\",15\n211,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"The example of Zany's new computer game illustrates the application of life-cycle costing.\"\"\",12\n213,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTING QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The Life Cycle Costing Quiz tests knowledge on Life-Cycle Costing.\"\"\",12\n208,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle cost is calculated in life-cycle costing to determine the total cost over the product's life-cycle.\"\"\",12\n207,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE STAGES\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle stages are considered in life-cycle costing to identify costs at different stages.\"\"\",12\n209,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle profit is calculated in life-cycle costing to determine the total profit over the product's life-cycle.\"\"\",12\n214,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFECYCLE PROFIT PER CUSTOMER\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz about calculating the lifecycle profit per customer is related to the concept of life-cycle costing.\"\"\",12\n591,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"COST PLUS PRICING METHODS\"\"\",\"\"\"Full cost plus pricing is a type of cost plus pricing method.\"\"\",9\n590,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: COST PLUS AND TARGET ROI\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz includes a question on calculating the selling price using Full Cost Plus Pricing.\"\"\",9\n1507,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR MIDHURST CO'S NEW AIR CONDITIONING UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ ON LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-Cycle Costing and Strategic Planning for Midhurst Co's New Air Conditioning Unit includes a Quiz on Life-Cycle Costing.\"\"\",8\n588,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Full Cost Plus Pricing has several advantages.\"\"\",7\n589,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Full Cost Plus Pricing has several disadvantages.\"\"\",7\n592,\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ ON FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Full Cost Plus Pricing is the subject of the quiz on full cost plus pricing.\"\"\",7\n587,\"\"\"PRICING DECISIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"FULL COST PLUS PRICING\"\"\",\"\"\"Full Cost Plus Pricing is a formula used in Pricing Decisions to determine product p